A germ layer lying remote from the surface of the embryo that gives rise to internal tissues such as gut.
An abnormal resistance to glucose, i.e., a reduction in the ability to maintain glucose levels in the blood stream within normal limits following oral or intravenous administration of glucose.
A layer of epithelium that lines the heart, blood vessels (ENDOTHELIUM, VASCULAR), lymph vessels (ENDOTHELIUM, LYMPHATIC), and the serous cavities of the body.

Single pavement layer of cells which line the luminal surface of the entire vascular system and regulate the transport of macromolecules and blood components from interstitium to lumen; this function has been most intensively studied in the blood capillaries.
A principal artery that originates in the aorta. It supplies blood to the muscular tissue of the heart.
The initial part of the pyloric canal of the stomach.  This site contains endocrine cells that produce gastrin and somatostatin.
The largest of the three paired salivary glands, located in front of the ear.
